<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910322-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>910322-0015.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- General Electric Co.:   Environmental Systems Unit   Wins $83 Million Contract</HL><DATE>03/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16</SO><CO>   AYP GE</CO><IN>POLLUTION CONTROL, WASTE MANAGEMENT SERVICES (POL)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><LP>   Allegheny Power System Inc. said it awarded apollution-control contract for more than $83 million to aGeneral Electric Co. unit as part of its effort to meetfederal clean-air standards.   The GE unit, General Electric Environmental Systems ofLebanon, Penn., will design and supply part of asmokestackscrubbing device in Allegheny Power's Harrisonplant in Clarksburg, West Virginia. The device removes sulfurdioxide from smokestack gases.</LP><TEXT>   Allegheny Power said it seeks to comply with the 1990amendments to the Clean Air Act. Its Harrison plant useshigh-sulfur coal and is among the 111 utilities that weretargeted by the acid-rain provisions of the legislation. Acidrain results from sulfur dioxide emissions into theatmosphere, largely from power plants.   The utility said the total cost for installing the deviceas well as containment facilities will total $800 million.The contract is subject to change or cancellation ifAllegheny Power's compliance plan isn't approved byregulatory authorities.</TEXT></DOC>